# LLM Agent — Quick Start

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:jido, path: Path.expand("..", __DIR__)},
  {:kino, "~> 0.16"}
])
```

## What this notebook builds

A working LLM agent in five cells. The model spec is a `Kino.Input` —
you pick the provider (local OpenAI-compat / Anthropic / OpenAI). Two
inline `Jido.Action` modules become the agent's tools. A `use Jido.Agent`
attaches `Jido.AI.ReAct` via `slices:` — that's the whole agent
declaration, no AI-specific macro.

The headline cell streams **ReAct steps live** into a `Kino.Frame`: you
type a question, click Ask, and watch the agent think, call tools,
receive results, and answer — driven by an out-of-band subscription you
control. See ADR 0022 v3.1 §7 (the `ask/3` + `ask_sync/3` API shape) and
§9 (the configurable-input rule) in `guides/adr/`.

> **Signal-level streaming, not token-level.** Each ReAct step (one
> LLM turn, one tool exec, one tool result) is one signal — the
> subscription dispatches one event per step. Token-by-token streaming
> through `ReqLLM.Generation.stream_text/3` is out of scope for v1.

## Setup — Demo.Jido

Boot a small Jido instance to start agents under, the same pattern as
the rest of the livebook set.

```elixir
defmodule Demo.Jido do
  use Jido, otp_app: :demo
end

case Demo.Jido.start_link() do
  {:ok, _pid} -> :started
  {:error, {:already_started, _pid}} -> :already_started
end
```

## Pick your model

A `Kino.Input.select/2` for the provider plus a `Kino.Input.password/1`
for the API key. The default is a local OpenAI-compatible endpoint at
`http://localhost:1234/v1` so the cells run end-to-end out of the box if
you have LM Studio / Ollama / vLLM up with a compatible model loaded.
Cloud providers need an API key.

```elixir
provider_input =
  Kino.Input.select(
    "Provider",
    [
      {:local, "Local OpenAI-compatible (LM Studio / Ollama / vLLM @ localhost:1234)"},
      {:anthropic, "Anthropic — claude-haiku-4-5 (paid)"},
      {:openai, "OpenAI — gpt-5-mini (paid)"}
    ]
  )

api_key_input = Kino.Input.password("API key (leave blank for local)")

Kino.Layout.grid([provider_input, api_key_input], columns: 1)
```

After changing either input, re-run the **Define the agent** cell below
so the new spec takes effect, then re-run the **Start the agent** cell
to spin up a fresh server.

## Define the tools

Two inline `use Jido.Action` modules — the agent's tools. The slice
converts each one into a `ReqLLM.Tool` via `Jido.AI.ToolAdapter` and
exposes them to the LLM.

```elixir
defmodule Demo.AI.Add do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "add",
    description: "Adds two integers and returns the sum.",
    schema: [
      a: [type: :integer, required: true, doc: "First addend"],
      b: [type: :integer, required: true, doc: "Second addend"]
    ]

  @impl true
  def run(%Jido.Signal{data: %{a: a, b: b}}, _slice, _opts, _ctx),
    do: {:ok, %{result: a + b}, []}
end

defmodule Demo.AI.Multiply do
  use Jido.Action,
    name: "multiply",
    description: "Multiplies two integers and returns the product.",
    schema: [
      a: [type: :integer, required: true, doc: "First factor"],
      b: [type: :integer, required: true, doc: "Second factor"]
    ]

  @impl true
  def run(%Jido.Signal{data: %{a: a, b: b}}, _slice, _opts, _ctx),
    do: {:ok, %{result: a * b}, []}
end
```

## Define the agent

A regular `use Jido.Agent`. It declares `name:`, a `path:` for its own
user-domain slice (unused — the AI slice owns its own `:ai` key), and
`slices: [{Jido.AI.ReAct, ...}]` carrying every LLM-specific value.

The slice's `config_schema/0` validates the keys at compile time; if you
typo `tools:` or pass an unknown field, `defmodule` raises `CompileError`
naming the slice and key. (See ADR 0022 §6 in `guides/adr/`.)

```elixir
provider_choice = Kino.Input.read(provider_input)
api_key_value = Kino.Input.read(api_key_input)

model_spec =
  case provider_choice do
    :local ->
      %{
        provider: :openai,
        id: "google/gemma-4-26b-a4b",
        base_url: "http://localhost:1234/v1"
      }

    :anthropic ->
      "anthropic:claude-haiku-4-5-20251001"

    :openai ->
      "openai:gpt-5-mini"
  end

# Local OpenAI-compatible servers ignore the api_key but still expect
# *something* in the Authorization header — pass a stub when the field
# is empty. ReqLLM uses the per-call :api_key as the highest-precedence
# source (above app config / env vars), so this `llm_opts:` plumbs your
# secret through verbatim. Multi-tenant callers set it per-call instead.
api_key_opt =
  case {provider_choice, api_key_value} do
    {:local, ""} -> "lm-studio"
    {:local, nil} -> "lm-studio"
    {_, key} when is_binary(key) and key != "" -> key
    _ -> ""
  end

defmodule LivebookAgent do
  use Jido.Agent,
    name: "livebook_ai",
    path: :state,
    slices: [
      {Jido.AI.ReAct,
       model: model_spec,
       tools: [Demo.AI.Add, Demo.AI.Multiply],
       system_prompt:
         "You are a concise arithmetic assistant. " <>
           "Use the `add` and `multiply` tools when calculations are needed, " <>
           "then state the final answer. Keep the answer to one sentence.",
       max_iterations: 5,
       max_tokens: 512,
       llm_opts: [api_key: api_key_opt]}
    ]
end

:ok
```

## Streaming output via subscription

A small helper module the run cell will use:

* `selector/1` — projects the slice's status, iteration, the
  in-flight tool calls, and the most recent tool message from the
  `ReqLLM.Context`. Returns `:skip` until a run is in flight so we
  don't see lifecycle signals from agent startup.
* `render/3` — pattern-matches on signal type + projection and
  appends one Markdown line to a `Kino.Frame` per ReAct step.
* `drain/3` — receives subscription dispatches in a loop until the
  slice settles `:completed` or `:failed`. No polling; no
  `Process.sleep`. A timeout renders a clear "timed out" line rather
  than hanging silently.

The dispatches arrive as `{:jido_subscription, sub_ref, %{signal_type:
type, result: {:ok, projection}}}` — the default `subscribe/4` shape.

```elixir
defmodule Demo.Streamer do
  @moduledoc false

  alias ReqLLM.Context

  @doc """
  Pure projecting selector — runs in the agent process, returns
  the slice fields the UI needs. `:skip` while no run is in flight.
  """
  def selector(state) do
    ai = state.agent.state.ai

    if is_nil(ai.request_id) do
      :skip
    else
      {:ok, project(ai)}
    end
  end

  @doc """
  Append one Markdown line to `frame` for the ReAct step described by
  `signal_type` + `projection`.
  """
  def render(frame, "ai.react.ask", _projection) do
    Kino.Frame.append(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("**Step 0** — _Thinking…_"))
  end

  def render(frame, "ai.react.llm.completed", %{
        status: :completed,
        result: result,
        iteration: iter
      }) do
    Kino.Frame.append(
      frame,
      Kino.Markdown.new(
        "**Step #{iter}** — _Final answer:_\n\n#{result || "_(model returned no text)_"}"
      )
    )
  end

  def render(frame, "ai.react.llm.completed", %{
        pending_tool_calls: [_ | _] = calls,
        iteration: iter
      }) do
    pretty =
      Enum.map_join(calls, "\n", fn c ->
        "- `#{c.name}(#{inspect(c.arguments)})`"
      end)

    Kino.Frame.append(
      frame,
      Kino.Markdown.new("**Step #{iter}** — _Model picked tools:_\n#{pretty}")
    )
  end

  def render(frame, "ai.react.llm.completed", %{iteration: iter, status: status}) do
    Kino.Frame.append(
      frame,
      Kino.Markdown.new("**Step #{iter}** — _LLM turn (#{status})._")
    )
  end

  def render(frame, "ai.react.tool.completed", %{
        last_tool_message: %{name: name, content: text}
      }) do
    truncated = String.slice(text || "", 0, 200)

    Kino.Frame.append(
      frame,
      Kino.Markdown.new("_Tool result_ — `#{name}` → `#{truncated}`")
    )
  end

  def render(frame, "ai.react.tool.completed", _projection) do
    Kino.Frame.append(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("_Tool result received._"))
  end

  def render(frame, "ai.react.failed", %{error: error}) do
    Kino.Frame.append(frame, Kino.Markdown.new("**Failed** — `#{inspect(error)}`"))
  end

  def render(_frame, _type, _projection), do: :noop

  @doc """
  Receive subscription dispatches until the slice settles. Returns
  `:done` on `:completed` / `:failed`, or `:timeout` after `deadline_ms`.
  """
  def drain(sub_ref, frame, deadline_ms) do
    receive do
      {:jido_subscription, ^sub_ref, %{signal_type: type, result: {:ok, projection}}} ->
        render(frame, type, projection)

        if projection.status in [:completed, :failed] do
          :done
        else
          drain(sub_ref, frame, deadline_ms)
        end

      {:jido_subscription, ^sub_ref, %{result: {:error, reason}}} ->
        Kino.Frame.append(
          frame,
          Kino.Markdown.new("_Selector error:_ `#{inspect(reason)}`")
        )

        drain(sub_ref, frame, deadline_ms)
    after
      deadline_ms ->
        Kino.Frame.append(
          frame,
          Kino.Markdown.new("**Timed out** waiting for completion (#{deadline_ms}ms).")
        )

        :timeout
    end
  end

  defp project(ai) do
    last_tool_message =
      if ai.context do
        ai.context
        |> Context.to_list()
        |> Enum.reverse()
        |> Enum.find_value(fn
          %{role: :tool} = msg -> format_tool_message(msg)
          _ -> nil
        end)
      end

    %{
      status: ai.status,
      iteration: ai.iteration,
      pending_tool_calls: ai.pending_tool_calls,
      result: ai.result,
      error: ai.error,
      last_tool_message: last_tool_message
    }
  end

  defp format_tool_message(%{role: :tool, name: name, content: parts}) do
    text =
      Enum.map_join(parts, "", fn
        %{type: :text, text: t} -> t
        _ -> ""
      end)

    %{name: name, content: text}
  end
end

:ok
```

## Start the agent

`Demo.Jido.start_agent/2` returns the pid that `Jido.AI.ask/3` and
`Jido.AI.ask_sync/3` accept. The id is unique per cell evaluation so
re-running this cell doesn't conflict with a running agent.

```elixir
agent_id = "llm-agent-#{System.unique_integer([:positive])}"
{:ok, agent_pid} = Demo.Jido.start_agent(LivebookAgent, id: agent_id)
:ok = Jido.AgentServer.await_ready(agent_pid)

agent_pid
```

## Ask — live ReAct steps in a Kino.Frame

The headline cell. Type a question, click Ask, watch each ReAct step
appear in the frame as it happens.

The wiring is the canonical out-of-band subscription pattern: the
caller subscribes to `"ai.react.**"` with a pure selector that projects
just what the UI needs, then `Jido.AI.ask/3` fires the run and the
receive loop drains dispatches. `ask/3` returns immediately with
`{:ok, request_id}` — the framework imposes no opinion on what the
caller filters for. Compare with `Jido.AI.ask_sync/3` in the next
section, which subscribes for the terminal transition only.

A good prompt for two-tool agents: `"What is (4 + 7) * 5?"` — the model
typically calls `add(4, 7)`, then `multiply(11, 5)`, then states 55.

The input + submit pair is wrapped in `Kino.Control.form/2`. Form
events carry the input values in `event.data`, so the listen
callback gets them directly — `Kino.Input.read/1` would fail here
because it can only run in the cell's main evaluation process, not
in a `Kino.listen` callback (which runs in its own task).

```elixir
output_frame = Kino.Frame.new()

ask_form =
  Kino.Control.form(
    [question: Kino.Input.text("Question", default: "What is (4 + 7) * 5?")],
    submit: "Ask"
  )

Kino.listen(ask_form, fn %{data: %{question: question}} ->
  Kino.Frame.render(output_frame, Kino.Markdown.new("_Asking:_ #{inspect(question)}"))

  {:ok, sub_ref} =
    Jido.AgentServer.subscribe(
      agent_pid,
      "ai.react.**",
      &Demo.Streamer.selector/1
    )

  case Jido.AI.ask(agent_pid, question) do
    {:ok, _request_id} ->
      _ = Demo.Streamer.drain(sub_ref, output_frame, 60_000)

    {:error, reason} ->
      Kino.Frame.append(
        output_frame,
        Kino.Markdown.new("**Error launching run:** `#{inspect(reason)}`")
      )
  end

  :ok = Jido.AgentServer.unsubscribe(agent_pid, sub_ref)
end)

Kino.Layout.grid([ask_form, output_frame])
```

## Same agent, sync — `ask_sync/3`

Two paths, one agent. `ask/3` is fire-and-forget — for streaming UIs,
multi-tenant request-id correlation, or any caller that wants the raw
signal stream. `ask_sync/3` is the convenience for "give me the
answer" — it subscribes internally for the terminal `:completed` /
`:failed` transition, blocks on the result, and returns just the final
text. Pick the shape that fits.

```elixir
sync_frame = Kino.Frame.new()

sync_form =
  Kino.Control.form(
    [question: Kino.Input.text("Question (sync)", default: "What is 12 multiplied by 7?")],
    submit: "Ask (sync)"
  )

Kino.listen(sync_form, fn %{data: %{question: question}} ->
  Kino.Frame.render(sync_frame, Kino.Markdown.new("_Working…_"))

  case Jido.AI.ask_sync(agent_pid, question, timeout: 60_000) do
    {:ok, text} ->
      Kino.Frame.render(
        sync_frame,
        Kino.Markdown.new("**Answer:** #{text || "_(no text)_"}")
      )

    {:error, reason} ->
      Kino.Frame.render(
        sync_frame,
        Kino.Markdown.new("**Error:** `#{inspect(reason)}`")
      )
  end
end)

Kino.Layout.grid([sync_form, sync_frame])
```

